# @madecki/ui Library Development Rules

This is the @madecki/ui component library. Follow these rules when making changes.

## Component Structure

All components follow this structure:
```
src/components/ComponentName/
├── ComponentName.tsx    # Main component implementation
└── index.ts            # Re-exports component and types
```

### Component Pattern

```tsx
import { ReactNode } from "react";

export interface ComponentNameProps {
  children?: ReactNode;
  variant?: "primary" | "secondary";
  className?: string;
}

export const ComponentName = ({
  children,
  variant = "primary",
  className = "",
}: ComponentNameProps) => {
  return (
    <div className={`base-classes ${className}`}>
      {children}
    </div>
  );
};

export default ComponentName;
```

### Export Pattern

In `src/components/ComponentName/index.ts`:
```tsx
export { ComponentName, type ComponentNameProps } from "./ComponentName";
```

In `src/components/index.ts`:
```tsx
export { ComponentName, type ComponentNameProps } from "./ComponentName";
```

In `src/index.ts`:
```tsx
export { ComponentName, type ComponentNameProps } from "./components";
```

## CRITICAL: Conventional commits (changelog source of truth)

**`CHANGELOG.md` is generated only by [semantic-release](https://github.com/semantic-release/semantic-release) on publish** from git history. **Do not hand-edit** release sections in **`CHANGELOG.md`**.

For any user-visible or breaking work, use valid [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) so the next release notes are correct:

- **`feat:`** — new behavior or API consumers can use (minor bump).
- **`fix:`** — bug fix (patch bump).
- **`perf:`** — performance (patch bump).
- **Breaking changes** — **`feat!:`** / **`fix!:`** and/or a footer line **`BREAKING CHANGE: description`** (major bump when analyzer detects it).
- Types like **`chore`**, **`docs`**, **`test`**, **`refactor`** do not usually appear in the changelog unless configured; use them for internal-only work.

[commitlint](https://commitlint.js.org/) runs on **`commit-msg`** (Husky) on **every `git commit`**, and again in **CI on each push to `main`** for the commits in that push. Invalid messages must be fixed before the commit is created (or CI will fail if **`--no-verify`** was used locally).

## CRITICAL: Commit when a task is finished

When you finish a coherent task (feature, fix, or doc/tooling change), **create a git commit** before moving on. Do not leave large uncommitted piles of work.

### Message quality

- Use a **Conventional Commits** subject that states **what** changed and **why** it matters to consumers or maintainers (not vague text like “updates” or “fixes”).
- In the **body**, list concrete changes (components, props, files, behavior) so the changelog and `git log` stay readable.
- Prefer **one commit per completed task**. If a task mixes unrelated concerns, split into separate commits.

### Breaking changes (extra care)

If consumers must **change their code** or **expect different runtime behavior**, treat it as **breaking**:

- Use **`feat!:`** or **`fix!:`** in the subject **and/or** a **`BREAKING CHANGE:`** paragraph in the body (after a blank line).
- In that paragraph, say **exactly** what breaks (e.g. removed prop, renamed export, new required prop) and what to do instead.
- Update **`llm-context.md`** and **`README.md`** in the **same** commit when the public API or usage patterns change.

### What usually is *not* breaking

Internal refactors, tests-only changes, or Storybook-only tweaks: use **`refactor:`**, **`test:`**, or **`chore:`** and **no** `!` / **`BREAKING CHANGE:`** unless the published API or documented contract actually changed.

## CRITICAL: Update LLM Context Files

When you add, remove, or modify components/props, you MUST update these files:

### 1. `llm-context.md` (root)
- Add/update component in the appropriate section
- Include all props with their types and defaults
- Update usage examples if needed

### 2. `cursor-rule-template.md` (root)
- Add component to the component list
- Keep it concise (this is a quick reference)

### 3. `README.md`
- Add full documentation for new components
- Update props tables if API changes

## File Update Checklist

When modifying components, update these files in order:

1. [ ] Component implementation (`src/components/*/`)
2. [ ] Component index (`src/components/*/index.ts`)
3. [ ] Components barrel (`src/components/index.ts`)
4. [ ] Main exports (`src/index.ts`)
5. [ ] **Conventional commit(s)** covering user-visible / breaking changes (changelog is generated on release — do not edit `CHANGELOG.md` by hand)
6. [ ] LLM context (`llm-context.md`)
7. [ ] Cursor template (`cursor-rule-template.md`)
8. [ ] README documentation (`README.md`)

## Design Tokens

Always use these tokens, never arbitrary values:

### Colors
`primary`, `darkgray`, `gray`, `lightgray`, `icongray`, `white`, `success`, `danger`, `warning`, `info`, `blue`, `neutral`

### Spacing
`1`-`21` (defined in tailwind-preset.ts and globals.css)

### Typography
`xs`, `sm`, `md`, `lg`, `xl`, `2xl`, `3xl`, `4xl`

### Border Radius
`sm`, `smb`, `md`, `mdb`, `circle`

## Dark Mode

All components must support dark mode using `dark:` prefix:
```tsx
<div className="bg-primary dark:bg-darkgray text-white">
```

## TypeScript

- Export all prop interfaces
- Use strict types (avoid `any`)
- Props should have sensible defaults
- Use `ReactNode` for children, not `React.ReactNode`

## Testing Changes

Before committing:
```bash
npm run typecheck  # Verify types
npm run build      # Verify build
npm run storybook  # Visual verification
```
